    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'll look into getting a kit. but is there any way to tell just by looking? like, is there a difference in how the leaves look if it's nitrogen vs something else stealing the nutrients?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you're looking for a bit of a \"leaf reading\" to diagnose your tomato plants' woes. While it's not as precise as a soil test, there are some general signs you can look for. If your plants are showing signs of nitrogen deficiency, you might notice that the older leaves at the bottom of the plant are turning yellow or pale green, while the newer leaves at the top remain a healthy green. This is because nitrogen is a mobile nutrient, meaning the plant can move it from older leaves to new growth when it's in short supply. On the other hand, if the entire plant is turning yellow, it could be a sign of a more systemic issue, such as a pH imbalance or a disease. In that case, the yellowing might be more widespread and not limited to just the older leaves. Remember, these are just general guidelines, and it's always best to confirm your findings with a soil test. Good luck, and may your tomato plants thrive in the face of adversity!",
